From cou.: 11 Fundamental SFG theory, data analysis,20–23 and our current experimental setup have been published previously.51,52 Briefly, an SFG system, manufactured by EKSPLA, was pumped with a Nd:YAG laser to generate the visible and infrared input beams. The fundamental output from the Nd:YAG laser was a 1064 nm beam with a 50 Hz repetition rate and a 30 ps pulse duration. The fixed frequency 532 nm visible input beam and frequency tunable infrared beam (2.3–10.0 μm) were produced from this 1064 nm beam and were over-lapped at the surface of polymer films on solid supports with input angles of 60° and 54° versus the surface normal, respectively. The beam energies for the visible and infrared lasers were 150 and 30 μJ, respectively. Both beam diameters were approximately 500 μm at the polymer film surface. The reflected SFG beam was directed through a monochromator after which the beam intensity was measured using a gated photomultiplier tube (Hamamatsu Corp., Hamamatsu City, Shizuoka, Japan). All SFG spectra were collected in the ssp (s-polarized SFG signal, s-polarized input visible, and p-polarized input infrared) and sps polarization combinations by scanning the infrared beam frequency while the monochromator was tuned automatically. For all SFG data collected, prism geometry was utilized, see Fig. 1. We repeated every experiment at least three times and for each time, at least three samples were prepared. The results are very reproducible and each spectrum presented in this work is the average of many SFG spectra with 100 averages per spectral point.
From Soup: 11 Fundamental SFG theory, data analysis, 20–23 and our current experimental setup have been published previously. 51,52 Briefly, an SFG system, manufactured by EKSPLA, was pumped with a Nd:YAG laser to generate the visible and infrared input beams. The fundamental output from the Nd:YAG laser was a 1064 nm beam with a 50 Hz repetition rate and a 30 ps pulse duration. The fixed frequency 532 nm visible input beam and frequency tunable infrared beam (2.3–10.0 μm) were produced from this 1064 nm beam and were over-lapped at the surface of polymer films on solid supports with input angles of 60° and 54° versus the surface normal, respectively. The beam energies for the visible and infrared lasers were 150 and 30 μJ, respectively. Both beam diameters were approximately 500 μm at the polymer film surface. The reflected SFG beam was directed through a monochromator after which the beam intensity was measured using a gated photomultiplier tube (Hamamatsu Corp., Hamamatsu City, Shizuoka, Japan). All SFG spectra were collected in the ssp (s-polarized SFG signal, s-polarized input visible, and p-polarized input infrared) and sps polarization combinations by scanning the infrared beam frequency while the monochromator was tuned automatically. For all SFG data collected, prism geometry was utilized, see Fig. 1 . We repeated every experiment at least three times and for each time, at least three samples were prepared. The results are very reproducible and each spectrum presented in this work is the average of many SFG spectra with 100 averages per spectral point.
