From cou.: 17 SFG has been applied to study a variety of polymer surfaces and interfaces.23,26,29,33,35,37,44,51,54–64 The detected signal intensity in an SFG experiment can be written in the following way:22In this equation, β is the angle between the reflected SFG signal and the surface normal, where ni(Ω) is the refractive index of medium i at frequency Ω. The variable χ(2)eff is the effective second order nonlinear susceptibility tensor of the material. I1(ω1) and I2(ω2) are the intensities of the input visible and infrared beams. When the infrared frequency, ω2, approaches a vibrational resonance, the effective nonlinear susceptibility tensor, χ(2)eff, can be written as:In this equation, χ(2)nr is the nonresonant term of χ(2)eff and is not dependent on the infrared light frequency. Aq, ωq, and Γq are the strength, resonant frequency, and damping coefficient of the qth vibrational mode, respectively. The values of these parameters may be obtained by fitting the SFG spectra. The above equations (Lorentzian function) are frequently utilized to fit SFG spectra. Further details of SFG theory can be found in previous publications.22,49,58,59,65,66
From Soup: 17 SFG has been applied to study a variety of polymer surfaces and interfaces. 23,26,29,33,35,37,44,51,54–64 The detected signal intensity in an SFG experiment can be written in the following way: 22 In this equation, β is the angle between the reflected SFG signal and the surface normal, where n i ( Ω ) is the refractive index of medium i at frequency Ω . The variable χ (2) eff is the effective second order nonlinear susceptibility tensor of the material. I 1 ( ω 1 ) and I 2 ( ω 2 ) are the intensities of the input visible and infrared beams. When the infrared frequency, ω 2 , approaches a vibrational resonance, the effective nonlinear susceptibility tensor, χ (2) eff , can be written as: In this equation, χ (2) nr is the nonresonant term of χ (2) eff and is not dependent on the infrared light frequency. A q , ω q , and Γ q are the strength, resonant frequency, and damping coefficient of the q th vibrational mode, respectively. The values of these parameters may be obtained by fitting the SFG spectra. The above equations (Lorentzian function) are frequently utilized to fit SFG spectra. Further details of SFG theory can be found in previous publications. 22,49,58,59,65,66
